{
  "contents": [
    "In language modeling, perplexity is a measure of how well a probability distribution predicts a sample of text.  Specifically, it quantifies the average uncertainty a language model has when predicting the next word in a sequence. A lower perplexity score indicates a better model \u2013 meaning it\u2019s more confident and accurate in its predictions and, therefore, has a more reliable probability distribution for the text.  Essentially, perplexity represents the inverse probability of the test set, normalized by the number of words, giving a sense of how surprised the model is by the observed text; the less surprised, the better the model\u2019s fit.",
    "In language modeling, perplexity is a measure of how well a probability distribution predicts a sample of text.  Specifically, it quantifies the average uncertainty a language model has when predicting the next word in a sequence. A lower perplexity score indicates a better model \u2013 meaning it\u2019s more confident and accurate in its predictions and, therefore, has a more reliable representation of the language it\u2019s trained on.  Essentially, perplexity represents the inverse probability of the test set, giving a sense of how surprised the model is by the observed text; a lower surprise is a better model."
  ],
